\section{\index{Combat}Combat}
\label{sec:combat}

\key{Surprise}: Both sides roll a d6. Your side is surprised if you
roll a 1 or a 2. If you're surprised, you'll have to skip the first
round. If the \index{Distance}distance between the two sides isn't
obvious, add the two dice and multiply the sum with \unit[10]{ft}. The
result is a distance of 20--\emph{\unit[120]{ft}}.
\marginnote[-4em]{Your \hyperref[sec:movement]{movement rate}
  determines whether surprised opponents can be attacked in the first
  round.}

\key{Initiative}: At the beginning of every round, both sides roll a
d6. The higer number begins. On a tie, players begin.
\marginnote[-1em]{The worst that can happen is that opponents go twice
  in a row.}

\key{Round}: Every round, you can move your movement rate and still do
something before or after your move. Typical \index{Action}actions:
melee or ranged attack, casting a spell or a miracle, read a
\index{Scroll}scroll, quaff a \index{Potion}potion. \index{Getting
  Up}Getting up also counts as a move. Dropping items you're holding,
drawing a weapon or saying things are free.\marginnote[-3em]{Anything
  may be \emph{attempted}, but chances of success and the time it
  takes will be determined at the table based on circumstances.}

\key{To Hit}: Roll a twenty-sided die (d20) and see if you hit. Add
your strength bonus when making a \index{Melee Attack}melee attack.
Add your dexterity bonus when making a \index{Ranged Attack}ranged
attack. Don't forget to add any magic bonuses, if you have a magic
weapon!\marginnote{The description of your class comes with a table
  where you'll see what you need to roll, depending on your level and
  the opponent's armor class. Roll that number or higher.}

\key[20 when attacking]{20}: If you roll a 20, you score a critical
hit which always hit and does max damage.

\key[30-sided die]{30}: Every player may use the thirty-sided die
(d30) in place of a d20 once per session. When rolling to hit, every
roll of twenty and above is a critical hit.

\key{Damage}: If you hit, roll damage using 1d6.\marginnote{We don't
  use variable weapon damage. All weapons do 1d6 damage.} Add your
strength bonus when making a melee attack. There is no bonus for
ranged attacks.

\key{Shield}: When carrying a shield\marginnote{At low levels, shields
  are crucial! Unfortunately, thieves and magic users may not carry
  shields.} and hit by a melee weapon or a magical force such as a
lightning bolt or a fire ball, you may sacrifice the shield such that
it absorbs all damage and is destroyed.

\key{Space}: In a wide corridor (\unit[10]{ft}) three people can fight
side by side. The space required depends on the weapons used, however:

