\section{\index{Movement}Movement}
\label{sec:movement}

\key{Movement Rate}: Humans have a movement rate (\key{MV}) of 12 --
that's \unit[120]{ft} per round (\unit[10]{s}) when \emph{running} or
\emph{fighting}. \marginnote[-1em]{Typical movement rates of other
  creatures: dwarf 6, halfling 9, elf 12, giant weasel 15, dog or wolf
  18, panther 21, galloping horse 24, flying hippogryph 36, flying
  pegasus 48.}

Proceeding slowly and methodically in the underworld slows you down
dramatically. MV~12 is only \unit[120]{ft} per turn (\unit[10]{min}).
That's the only way to have a fair chance of drawing maps and avoiding
traps.

\key{Carrying Capacity}: You can carry as many significant items as
your \emph{strength}.\marginnote{Typical items: armor, a weapon, a
  book, a potion, a torch, a quiver, a scroll. There's no difference
  between light and heavy items. Clothing, bags or backpacks don't
  count.} If you carry more, each extra item adds -1 to hit and to
saving throws.

\key{Stuff}: It takes a lot of small things to count as an item: a
hundred gold coins, gems, rings, amulets and the like count as a
single item.

\section{Reputation}
\label{sec:reputation}

\key{Reputation}: Fame and honor can be earned everywhere. Even the
\index{Gods!Reputation}gods are interested in the deeds of mortals.
Reputation is tracked separately for all the gods, towns and
factions.\marginnote{The referee maintains a list of gods, towns and
  factions and the respective reputation for each character.} The
higher your reputation, the harder it is to increase it. In order to
gain reputation, roll higher than your current reputation. The
starting reputation is 0. Thus, the first time reputation increases,
no roll is required.Reputation can be good or bad. The gods take an
interest in blasphemers, too!\marginnote{The higher your reputation,
  the harder it will be to increase.} Usually, reputation will not
change for more than ±1 per session.

